        <h2>Bihar, The Land of Monasteries</h2>
        <p>The land of diverse cultures, traditions, and faiths, Bihar is a state in eastern India, bordered by Nepal to the north, West Bengal to the northeast, and Uttar Pradesh to the west. It is the third-largest state by population and the twelfth largest by area in the country. Bihar holds immense historical and spiritual significance, being the place where Gautam Buddha, the founder of Buddhism, attained enlightenment. The town of Bodhgaya, home to the sacred Bodhi Tree, is one of the most important Buddhist pilgrimage sites globally. Additionally, Bihar is home to the revered Tirthankaras of Jainism. The state boasts a rich historical heritage, including several ancient sites and the oldest educational institution in India, Nalanda University. Bihar is a must-visit destination for history enthusiasts and spiritual seekers alike, with its abundance of religious sites and pilgrimages. Remarkably, nearly 58% of Bihar's population is under the age of 25, making it the state with the highest proportion of young people in India.</p>
