    <section id="transportation">
        <h2>Transportation & Connectivity</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Air Connectivity:</b> Bihar is served by multiple airports, with the primary ones being Jay Prakash Narayan International Airport in Patna and Gaya International Airport in Gaya. These airports offer regular domestic flights to major cities like Delhi, Mumbai, Kolkata, and Bangalore, as well as international flights to countries such as Thailand, Sri Lanka, and Bhutan. The state's air connectivity has been steadily improving, with new routes and enhanced airport facilities being developed.</li>
            <li>Rail Connectivity: Bihar has an extensive railway network, with Patna Junction being one of the busiest railway stations in India. The state is connected to all major cities in India, including Delhi, Kolkata, Mumbai, and Chennai, through a network of express and superfast trains. Bihar's railway stations, including those in Gaya, Muzaffarpur, Bhagalpur, and Darbhanga, are key junctions that facilitate smooth travel within the state and to neighboring regions. The rail network is a crucial mode of transportation for both passengers and freight.</li>
            <li>Road Connectivity: Bihar's road network has seen significant improvements in recent years, with national highways, state highways, and rural roads connecting various parts of the state. The Grand Trunk Road (NH 19), one of the oldest and longest roads in India, passes through Bihar, linking it to major cities like Delhi and Kolkata. The state government has been actively working on improving road infrastructure through projects that focus on building new highways, bridges, and expressways. Regular bus services, including state-run and private operators, connect Bihar with neighboring states like Uttar Pradesh, Jharkhand, and West Bengal.</li>
        </ul>
